{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The content passed to the summary-generation step includes data retrieved from all three sources.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: the failure is at a module handoff boundary (collectors -> aggregator -> summary input), not a single-function algorithm. REAL-INFRA: not required as minimum; source clients can be in-process fakes. MOCK-HIDE: pure unit tests of merge logic can miss wiring mistakes where one collector is never invoked or dropped before handoff. LLM-DEP: no, this behavior is about input assembly, not model judgment. MULTI-STEP: no. Rejection gate: System is rejected because behavior text only requires that content passed to summary generation includes all three sources, which can be validated without real network/OS.","test_description":"Wire real collection/orchestration modules together with three fake source adapters returning distinct sentinel fields; execute one report run up to the summary-generation call and assert the exact payload handed to that step contains all three source sections and values.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When one data source is unavailable, the report is produced with a `data unavailable` note for that section rather than aborting.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: this is cross-module error propagation (source failure -> orchestrator fallback -> report composition). REAL-INFRA: a real network outage is not strictly required to catch the core failure; an in-process adapter raising timeout/connection errors exercises the same branch. MOCK-HIDE: unit tests of fallback formatter alone would miss abort behavior in orchestration. LLM-DEP: no, correctness is fallback behavior, not model quality. MULTI-STEP: no. Rejection gate: System is rejected because behavior text focuses on fallback semantics ('data unavailable' note rather than aborting), which are reproducible via controlled adapter failures.","test_description":"Run orchestration with two healthy fake sources and one fake source that raises an availability error; assert run completes, report object/text includes a `data unavailable` marker only for that section, and pipeline does not terminate early.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The narrative summary accurately represents the key values present in the input data.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: yes. The behavior explicitly evaluates summary accuracy, which depends on model output content and can vary run to run. Deterministic stubs would hide hallucination/omission/misattribution failures. MOCK-MISS and MOCK-HIDE both indicate lower levels are insufficient for this behavior. MULTI-STEP: only one model judgment is required, so Workflow is not mandatory. Rejection gate: Workflow is rejected because behavior text describes one summary-generation outcome, not a sequence of multiple agentic decisions.","test_description":"Use a fixed hard-case canary set of input datasets with known key facts; call the real summary-generation model and score output against required fact-preservation checks (presence/correctness of key metrics, issue counts, deployment status) with repeat runs to detect unstable misrepresentation.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Test explicitly requires real model output quality, matching Agentic minimum.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.75,"Workflow":0.1}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A complete report — from data collection through email delivery — reaches the configured recipient's inbox correctly.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"REAL-INFRA: yes. This boundary includes real HTTP/API calls and real email delivery/inbox receipt; in-process fakes can miss SMTP/API/auth/format/routing failures. MOCK-HIDE: mocked mail transport often passes while real provider rejects or misroutes. LLM-DEP: not required for the core assertion (inbox delivery), so Agentic is not minimum. MULTI-STEP: no required multi-agent sequence. Rejection gate: Agentic is rejected because behavior text validates end-to-end delivery to inbox, not summary quality/model judgment.","test_description":"Execute scheduled job in a staging-like environment against real reachable source endpoints (or realistic test instances) and a real test mailbox; assert a message arrives to configured recipient, with expected subject/body attachment structure and traceable run timestamp.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.78,"Agentic":0.08,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the email delivery service is unreachable, the generated report is saved to a local file and delivery is retried on the next scheduled run.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"REAL-INFRA: yes for minimum confidence, because failure involves transport unreachability plus durable local-file fallback and subsequent scheduled retry behavior across runs. MOCK-HIDE: mocked mail and filesystem can hide real persistence/path/permission/locking/scheduler boundary issues. LLM-DEP: no, behavior is delivery-fallback orchestration. MULTI-STEP: no agentic chain. Rejection gate: Integration is rejected because behavior text requires retry on the next scheduled run with local file persistence, a boundary where real OS/filesystem/scheduler behavior can be the actual failure source.","test_description":"Run job with email endpoint intentionally unreachable in a real test environment; verify report is written to configured local fallback path, then trigger the next scheduled run after restoring email service and assert queued report is re